{"title_page": "Tommy Vext", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Tommy Vext\n| image           = Bad Wolves - Rock am Ring 2019-1109.jpg\n| caption         = Tommy Vext with [[Bad Wolves]] live at [[Rock am Ring]] 2019\n| image_size      = \n| landscape       = yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_name      = Thomas Cummings\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1982|04|15}}\n| birth_place     = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], US\n| instrument      = Vocals\n| genre           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]\n* [[thrash metal]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n* [[speed metal]]\n* [[groove metal]]\n* [[metalcore]]\n* [[death metal]]\n* [[alternative metal]]\n}}\n| occupation      = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n}}\n| years_active    = 2000\u2013present\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Eleven Seven Music|Eleven Seven]]\n* [[Century Media Records|Century Media]]\n* [[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Bad Wolves]]\n* [[Snot (band)|Snot]]\n* [[Divine Heresy]]\n* [[God Forbid]]\n}}\n| website         = {{URL|badwolvesnation.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Cummings''' (born April 15, 1982), better known under the [[stage name]] '''Tommy Vext''', is an American [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] singer and songwriter known for being the lead vocalist of [[Bad Wolves]], [[Snot (band)|Snot]], [[Divine Heresy]] and Westfield Massacre. He was also the fill-in vocalist for the multi-platinum selling heavy metal band [[Five Finger Death Punch]] during their European Arena tour in 2017 when [[Ivan Moody (vocalist)|Ivan L. Moody]] left the tour to check into rehab.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalinjection.net/latest-news/drama/ivan-moody-to-sit-out-five-finger-death-punch-european-tour-checks-back-into-rehab|title=Ivan Moody To Sit Out Five Finger Death Punch European Tour, Checks Back Into Rehab - Metal Injection|date=June 14, 2017|website=Metalinjection.net|accessdate=October 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/five-finger-death-punch-ivan-moody-exits-tour-tommy-vext-fill-in-vocals/|title=Five Finger Death Punch's Ivan Moody Exits Euro Tour, Tommy Vext to Fill In|website=Loudwire.com|accessdate=October 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n[[File:20170614-046-Nova Rock 2017-Five Finger Death Punch-Tommy Vext.jpg|thumb|Tommy Vext with Bad Wolves live at [[Nova Rock]] 2017.]]\n=== Early career<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|title=The Ex Man Podcast 06 - Tommy Vext (Bad Wolves, ex-Westfield Massacre, ex-Snot, ex-Divine Heresy)|url=https://soundcloud.com/doc-coyle/the-ex-man-podcast-06-tommy-vext-westfield-massacre-ex-snot-ex-divine-heresy|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref> ===\nVext began his music career in [[Brooklyn]], New York as a teenager singing in local hardcore bands and engaging in freestyle rap battles with the neighborhood's preeminent hopefuls. Being too young, he had to sneak into clubs even for his own shows. In 1996, he formed the band Maniacal Disciple with friends Jim Donovan, Steve Perlmutter and Mike Kontaras, eventually changing their name to \"Vext\" (a word he found in [[Wu-Tang Clan]]'s lyrics), which eventually became his nickname after he started to be known as \"Tommy Vext\" in the New York hardcore scene. Vext was a local buzz band, playing shows at [[CBGB]], The Continental, and Lamours. They also opened for [[Biohazard (band)|Biohazard]], [[Candiria]] and many others. In 2005, at the [[Roadrunner Records]] 25th-anniversary show, Vext was invited to sing with [[Corey Taylor]] of [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]].<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=Roadrunner United Corey Taylor and Tommy Vext Singing|date=2008-12-12|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DNBdBNS_Clo|volume=|pages=|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Divine Heresy<ref name=\":0\" />===\nIn 2006, Vext was recruited by [[Dino Cazares]] of [[Fear Factory]] to front his new band [[Divine Heresy]]. Their debut studio album ''[[Bleed the Fifth]]'' was released in the United States on August 28, 2007 by [[Century Media Records]]. The album was produced by former [[Machine Head (band)|Machine Head]] and [[Soulfly]] guitarist, [[Logan Mader]].\n\n''Bleed the Fifth'' enjoyed a warm welcome from both the fans and the press. Dom Lawson of ''[[Metal Hammer]]'' summarized his review by saying \"All in all, the portly pioneer has hit the bull's-eye and it's going to be fascinating to see what happens next\", awarding an eight out of a possible 10.<ref name=\"Bleed the Fifth reviews\">{{cite web\n|title=Bleed the Fifth reviews\n|publisher=[[Roadrunner Records|RoadrunnerRecords.co.uk]]\n|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.co.uk/artists/DivineHeresy/press.aspx\n|accessdate=2007-12-30 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071221055555/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.co.uk/artists/DivineHeresy/press.aspx |archivedate = December 21, 2007}}</ref> Eduardo Rivadavia of [[AllMusic]] felt the album \"strikes a near-perfect balance between confirmation (reminding fans of Cazares' abilities and unique vision) and innovation (he even plays a few guitar solos!)\".<ref name=\" Bleed the Fifth AMG\">{{cite web\n|title=''Bleed the Fifth'' > Review\n|author=Rivadavia, Eduardo\n|publisher=[[AllMusic]]\n|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1183429|pure_url=yes}}\n|accessdate=2007-12-30}}</ref> Scott Alisoglu of [[Blabbermouth.net]] summarized his review claiming the album is \"one tough son of a bitch that may still have you humming melodies long after you've ejected the disc\".<ref name=\"Bleed the Fifth RR\">{{cite web\n |title       = ''Bleed the Fifth'' Roadrunner review\n |author      = Alisoglu, Scott\n |publisher   = [[Blabbermouth.net]]\n |url         = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/showreview.aspx?reviewID=1207\n |accessdate  = 2007-12-31\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071017154511/http://roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/showreview.aspx?reviewID=1207\n |archivedate = 2007-10-17\n}}</ref> Chad Bowar of [[Dotdash|About.com]] commented \"Great musicianship, good songs and excellent production make this a very respectable debut\".<ref name=\"Bleed The Fifth ABOUT\">{{cite web\n|title=''Bleed The Fifth'' About.com review\n|author=Boward, Chad\n|publisher=[[Dotdash|About.com]]\n|url=http://heavymetal.about.com/od/cdreviews/fr/divinehereseybl.htm\n|accessdate=2007-12-31}}</ref>\n\nVext wrote the majority of the lyrics, {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} which are about personal strifes and how people overcome them. Much of the lyrical content was influenced by the [[Book of Revelation]], natural disasters, war, and terrorism.<ref name=\"Divine Heresy: Heretic Anthems\">{{cite web\n|title=Divine Heresy: Heretic Anthems\n|author= Donnelly, Justin\n|publisher=The Metal Forge\n|date=2007-09-12\n|url=http://www.themetalforge.com/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=1299\n|accessdate=2007-12-30}}</ref>\n\nDue to unresolvable differences with [[Dino Cazares]], Vext parted with [[Divine Heresy]] in 2008. The highly publicised split left both the fans and the press confused. In an exclusive \"Metal Injection\" interview, Vext explained the real reasons behind his departure from the band: \n{{Quotation| I've been suffering the indignities of Dino's massive ego for as long as I've worked with him, and unfortunately, everything I've heard about him had eventually come to fruition, and he is exactly as he's been portrayed as by his ex-band members. And this happening now is the same reason why he's not in Fear Factory anymore. It was a stepping stone in my life and I'm moving on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2008/05/01/the-divine-heresy-soap-opera-continues/|title=THE DIVINE HERESY SOAP OPERA CONTINUES|date=1 May 2008|website=Metalsucks.com|accessdate=31 May 2016}}</ref> |Tommy Vext}}\n\nLater bassist Joe Payne and drummer [[Tim Yeung]] both broke ties with Dino and on July 27, 2015, in an interview with [[MetalSucks]], Cazares confirmed that he was the only remaining member of Divine Heresy.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2015/07/27/109-dino-cazares-of-fear-factory/ | title=#109: Dino Cazares of Fear Factory | publisher=[[MetalSucks]] | date=July 27, 2015 | accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Snot<ref name=\":0\" />===\n[[Snot (band)|Snot]] is an American [[Heavy metal music|metal]] band from [[Santa Barbara, California]]. Formed in 1995, the band released their debut studio album ''[[Get Some (album)|Get Some]]'' with founding vocalist [[Lynn Strait]] in 1997 and disbanded after his death in 1998. In 2008, the band reformed, with Vext on vocals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Reunited Snot Releases New Song, Announces Tour With DEVILDRIVER |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=102395 |publisher=[[blabbermouth.net]] |date=August 7, 2008 |accessdate=April 15, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081223014922/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=102395 |archivedate=December 23, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Snot has played a number of shows fronted by Vext, including a fall 2008 tour in the United States, supporting [[DevilDriver]]. When later original guitarist [[Sonny Mayo]] left the band, Snot went on hiatus again.\n\nOn February 11, 2014, Snot reunited the second time at the [[Whisky a Go Go]] in Hollywood.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/reunited-snot-to-play-first-show-in-five-years-next-month/ |title=Reunited SNOT To Play First Show in Five Years Next Month |date=January 13, 2014 |publisher=[[blabbermouth.net]] |accessdate=February 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/video-reunited-snot-plays-first-show-in-five-years/ |title=Video: Reunited SNOT Plays First Show In Five Years |date=February 15, 2014 |publisher=[[blabbermouth.net]] |accessdate=February 15, 2014}}</ref> This second reunion line-up once again featured Vext, Mayo, Doling, Fahnestock and Miller. They went on to play three more shows in the Southern California area before once again going quiet.\n\n=== Vext ===\nIn 2011 Tommy Vext reformed Vext with members of [[Mutiny Within]], (Bill Fore, and Andrew Jacobs); along with guitar virtuoso [[Angel Vivaldi]]. They released the EP titled ''Impermanence.'' in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.angelvivaldiofficial.com/about |title=angelvivaldi. &#124; o f f i c i a l w e b s i t e |publisher=Angelvivaldiofficial.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-30}}</ref>\nBy 2013 Vivaldi and Jacobs had left the project, with Billy DiNapoli taking over on guitars.  They released an EP ''Broke is the New Black''.<ref>{{cit web|url=http://rip-fred-marques.blogspot.com/2014/02/vext-broke-is-new-black-ep-2013.html |date= |accessdate=2018-10-29}}</ref>\n\nTommy then had gone on tour with [[Mayhem Festival]] '2013 as a cook, and moved to Los Angeles after the tour.\n\n=== Westfield Massacre<ref name=\":0\" />===\nAfter his stint with Snot, Vext moved on and formed a new band known as \"Westfield Massacre\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metalinjection.net/av/former-divine-heresy-members-launch-the-westfield-massacre/ |title=Westfield Massacre |date=April 29, 2016 |publisher=metalinjection.net |accessdate=April 29, 2016}}</ref> The band released their self-titled debut album on Urban Yeti Records 2016. In 2017, Vext began working on a side project with former [[DevilDriver]] drummer [[John Boecklin]] Vext left Westfield while he was on tour with Five Finger Death Punch.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theprp.com/2017/06/12/news/westfield-massacre-replace-frontman-tommy-vext-amid-drama/|title=Westfield Massacre |publisher=ThePrP.com|date=June 12, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n=== Bad Cats ===\nIn 2016, Vext formed a new band, known as \"[[Bad Wolves]]\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.riffrelevant.com/2017/05/01/bad-wolves-pastpresent-westfield-massacre-god-forbid-devildriver-etc-members-premiere-learn-to-live-video/ |title=Bad Wolves |date=May 1, 2017 |publisher=riffrelevant.com |accessdate=May 1, 2017}}</ref> with former [[DevilDriver]] drummer [[John Boecklin]]. Guitarists Doc Coyle (Vagus Nerve, [[God Forbid]]) and Chris Cain ([[Bury Your Dead]]), and later, bassist Kyle Konkiel formerly of [[In This Moment]] were recruited for the project. During the summer of 2016, they entered AudioHammer Studios with longtime collaborator Mark Lewis ([[Trivium (band)|Trivium]], [[All That Remains (band)|All That Remains]]) and tracked what would become the group's debut studio album. On May 2, 2017, Bad Wolves independently premiered a song titled \"Learn to Live\" accompanied by a music video<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metalinjection.net/video/bad-wolves-ex-god-forbid-ex-devildriver-premieres-way-djenty-learn-to-live/ |title=Video: Learn To Live |date=May 2, 2017 |publisher=metalinjection.net |accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref> The video was streamed over 600,000 times. In November 2017, it was announced<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/bad-wolves-feat-former-devildriver-god-forbid-divine-heresy-members-debut-album-due-in-spring/\n  |title=Bad Wolves Get Signed |date=November 2, 2017 |publisher=Blabbermouth.net }}</ref> that Bad Wolves signed with [[Eleven Seven Music]] and [[Zoltan Bathory]], the founding guitarist of [[Five Finger Death Punch]], took them under his wings as the band's manager.\n\nThe band released their debut studio album, ''[[Disobey]]'' on May 11, 2018 through [[Eleven Seven Music]].<ref name=\"Loudwire\"/><ref name=\"Loudwire\">{{cite web | url=http://loudwire.com/bad-wolves-toast-to-the-ghost-new-song-debut-album/ | title=BAD WOLVES 'TOAST TO THE GHOST' IN NEW SONG, ANNOUNCE DEBUT ALBUM | website=Loudwire.com | date=3 November 2017 | accessdate=3 February 2018 | author=Hill, John}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theprp.com/2018/03/23/news/bad-wolves-share-acoustic-cover-zombie-detail-debut-album-disobey/|title=Bad Wolves Share Acoustic Cover Of \"Zombie\", Detail Debut Album \"Disobey\"|publisher=theprp.com|accessdate=March 23, 2018|date=March 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe album reached number 23 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. In May 2017, Bad Wolves released their debut single, \"Learn to Live\".<ref name=\"learn2live\">{{cite web|title=BAD WOLVES Feat. Former DEVILDRIVER, GOD FORBID, DIVINE HERESY Members: 'Learn To Live' Video Released|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/bad-wolves-feat-former-devildriver-god-forbid-divine-heresy-members-learn-to-live-video-released/|website=[[Blabbermouth]]|accessdate=2018-03-01|date=May 2017}}</ref> In November 2017, Bad Wolves released their second single, \"Toast to the Ghost\".<ref name=\"Loudwire\"/> On January 18, 2018, they released a third single, which was a cover of \"[[Zombie (song)#Bad Wolves version|Zombie]]\" (originally by [[The Cranberries]]), which charted on multiple [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' charts]].<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8097436/bad-wolves-cranberries-zombie-rock-charts | title=Bad Wolves' Cover of The Cranberries' 'Zombie' Roars Onto Rock Charts | website=Billboard.com | date=31 January 2018 | accessdate=3 February 2018 | author=Rutherford, Kevin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Bad-Wolves-Cover-of-The-Cranberries-ZOMBIE-Goes-Global-20180130 | title=Bad Wolves' Cover of The Cranberries' ZOMBIE Goes Global | website=Broadway World | date=30 January 2018 | accessdate=4 February 2018}}</ref> The night of her death, [[Dolores O'Riordan]] left a voice message to her friend, record label executive Dan Waite, where she offered to \"sing on it\" on the cover that Waite had previously given O'Riordan to listen to and accredit. [[TMZ]] published this voice message on April 5, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8289027/dolores-oriordan-cranberries-final-recording-voicemail-audio |title=Voicemail from Cranberries Singer Dolores O'Riordan Emerges |website=www.billboard.com|date=September 19, 2019 |accessdate=September 19, 2019}}</ref> A music video was released on February 22. The song topped the US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock Songs]] chart, while the music video was viewed more than 170 million times. The single is certified platinum in Canada and the United States and gold in Germany.\n\nThe band toured with [[Five Finger Death Punch]], [[Shinedown]], [[Breaking Benjamin]], and [[Starset]] for the first half of 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theprp.com/2018/02/06/news/five-finger-death-punch-shinedown-starset-bad-wolves-tour-announced/|title=Five Finger Death Punch, Shinedown, Starset & Bad Wolves Tour Announced {{!}} Theprp.com|date=2018-02-06|work=Theprp.com|access-date=2018-02-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\nBad Wolves became the first rock band in 2018 to reach platinum status for their cover song, \"[[Zombie (song)#Bad Wolves version|Zombie]]\".<ref name=\"Platinum\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/bad-wolves-video-of-zombie-platinum-plaque-presentation-in-camden-new-jersey/|title=BAD WOLVES: Video Of 'Zombie' Platinum-Plaque Presentation In Camden, New Jersey|accessdate=2018-09-06|date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Vext ===\n\n* 2004: ''Cast The First Stone''\n* 2012: ''Impermanence''\n\n=== God Forbid ===\n\n* 2004: ''[[Gone Forever]]'' (guest vocals on \"Soul Engraved\")\n\n=== Divine Heresy ===\n\n* 2007: ''[[Bleed the Fifth]]''\n\n=== Westfield Massacre ===\n\n* 2016: ''Westfield Massacre''\n\n=== Bad Wolves ===\n\n* 2018: ''[[Disobey]]''\n* 2019: ''[[N.A.T.I.O.N.]]''\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n* ''Twinkle Twinkle Little Star'' (short film) (2016) (as Drug Dealer)<ref>{{Citation|title=Twinkle Twinkle Little Star|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5535868/|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Commonscat}}\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vext, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American rock singers]]\n[[Category:African-American male singers]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Tommy Vext\n| image           = Bad Wolves - Rock am Ring 2019-1109.jpg\n| caption         = Tommy Vext with [[Bad Wolves]] live at [[Rock am Ring]] 2019\n| image_size      = \n| landscape       = yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_name      = Thomas Cummings\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1982|04|15}}\n| birth_place     = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], US\n| instrument      = Vocals\n| genre           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]\n* [[thrash metal]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n* [[speed metal]]\n* [[groove metal]]\n* [[metalcore]]\n* [[death metal]]\n* [[alternative metal]]\n}}\n| occupation      = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n}}\n| years_active    = 2000\u2013present\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Eleven Seven Music|Eleven Seven]]\n* [[Century Media Records|Century Media]]\n* [[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Bad Wolves]]\n* [[Snot (band)|Snot]]\n* [[Divine Heresy]]\n* [[God Forbid]]\n}}\n| website         = {{URL|badwolvesnation.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Cummings''' (born April 15, 1982), better known under the [[stage name]] '''Tommy Vext''', is an American [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] singer and songwriter known for being the lead vocalist of [[Bad Wolves]], [[Snot (band)|Snot]], [[Divine Heresy]] and Westfield Massacre. He was also the fill-in vocalist for the multi-platinum selling heavy metal band [[Five Finger Death Punch]] during their European Arena tour in 2017 when [[Ivan Moody (vocalist)|Ivan L. Moody]] left the tour to check into rehab.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalinjection.net/latest-news/drama/ivan-moody-to-sit-out-five-finger-death-punch-european-tour-checks-back-into-rehab|title=Ivan Moody To Sit Out Five Finger Death Punch European Tour, Checks Back Into Rehab - Metal Injection|date=June 14, 2017|website=Metalinjection.net|accessdate=October 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/five-finger-death-punch-ivan-moody-exits-tour-tommy-vext-fill-in-vocals/|title=Five Finger Death Punch's Ivan Moody Exits Euro Tour, Tommy Vext to Fill In|website=Loudwire.com|accessdate=October 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n[[File:20170614-046-Nova Rock 2017-Five Finger Death Punch-Tommy Vext.jpg|thumb|Tommy Vext with Bad Wolves live at [[Nova Rock]] 2017.]]\n=== Early career<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|title=The Ex Man Podcast 06 - Tommy Vext (Bad Wolves, ex-Westfield Massacre, ex-Snot, ex-Divine Heresy)|url=https://soundcloud.com/doc-coyle/the-ex-man-podcast-06-tommy-vext-westfield-massacre-ex-snot-ex-divine-heresy|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref> ===\nVext began his music career in [[Brooklyn]], New York as a teenager singing in local hardcore bands and engaging in freestyle rap battles with the neighborhood's preeminent hopefuls. Being too young, he had to sneak into clubs even for his own shows. In 1996, he formed the band Maniacal Disciple with friends Jim Donovan, Steve Perlmutter and Mike Kontaras, eventually changing their name to \"Vext\" (a word he found in [[Wu-Tang Clan]]'s lyrics), which eventually became his nickname after he started to be known as \"Tommy Vext\" in the New York hardcore scene. Vext was a local buzz band, playing shows at [[CBGB]], The Continental, and Lamours. They also opened for [[Biohazard (band)|Biohazard]], [[Candiria]] and many others. In 2005, at the [[Roadrunner Records]] 25th-anniversary show, Vext was invited to sing with [[Corey Taylor]] of [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]].<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=Roadrunner United Corey Taylor and Tommy Vext Singing|date=2008-12-12|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DNBdBNS_Clo|volume=|pages=|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Divine Heresy<ref name=\":0\" />===\nIn 2006, Vext was recruited by [[Dino Cazares]] of [[Fear Factory]] to front his new band [[Divine Heresy]]. Their debut studio album ''[[Bleed the Fifth]]'' was released in the United States on August 28, 2007 by [[Century Media Records]]. The album was produced by former [[Machine Head (band)|Machine Head]] and [[Soulfly]] guitarist, [[Logan Mader]].\n\n''Bleed the Fifth'' enjoyed a warm welcome from both the fans and the press. Dom Lawson of ''[[Metal Hammer]]'' summarized his review by saying \"All in all, the portly pioneer has hit the bull's-eye and it's going to be fascinating to see what happens next\", awarding an eight out of a possible 10.<ref name=\"Bleed the Fifth reviews\">{{cite web\n|title=Bleed the Fifth reviews\n|publisher=[[Roadrunner Records|RoadrunnerRecords.co.uk]]\n|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.co.uk/artists/DivineHeresy/press.aspx\n|accessdate=2007-12-30 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071221055555/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.co.uk/artists/DivineHeresy/press.aspx |archivedate = December 21, 2007}}</ref> Eduardo Rivadavia of [[AllMusic]] felt the album \"strikes a near-perfect balance between confirmation (reminding fans of Cazares' abilities and unique vision) and innovation (he even plays a few guitar solos!)\".<ref name=\" Bleed the Fifth AMG\">{{cite web\n|title=''Bleed the Fifth'' > Review\n|author=Rivadavia, Eduardo\n|publisher=[[AllMusic]]\n|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1183429|pure_url=yes}}\n|accessdate=2007-12-30}}</ref> Scott Alisoglu of [[Blabbermouth.net]] summarized his review claiming the album is \"one tough son of a bitch that may still have you humming melodies long after you've ejected the disc\".<ref name=\"Bleed the Fifth RR\">{{cite web\n |title       = ''Bleed the Fifth'' Roadrunner review\n |author      = Alisoglu, Scott\n |publisher   = [[Blabbermouth.net]]\n |url         = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/showreview.aspx?reviewID=1207\n |accessdate  = 2007-12-31\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071017154511/http://roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/showreview.aspx?reviewID=1207\n |archivedate = 2007-10-17\n}}</ref> Chad Bowar of [[Dotdash|About.com]] commented \"Great musicianship, good songs and excellent production make this a very respectable debut\".<ref name=\"Bleed The Fifth ABOUT\">{{cite web\n|title=''Bleed The Fifth'' About.com review\n|author=Boward, Chad\n|publisher=[[Dotdash|About.com]]\n|url=http://heavymetal.about.com/od/cdreviews/fr/divinehereseybl.htm\n|accessdate=2007-12-31}}</ref>\n\nVext wrote the majority of the lyrics, {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} which are about personal strifes and how people overcome them. Much of the lyrical content was influenced by the [[Book of Revelation]], natural disasters, war, and terrorism.<ref name=\"Divine Heresy: Heretic Anthems\">{{cite web\n|title=Divine Heresy: Heretic Anthems\n|author= Donnelly, Justin\n|publisher=The Metal Forge\n|date=2007-09-12\n|url=http://www.themetalforge.com/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=1299\n|accessdate=2007-12-30}}</ref>\n\nDue to unresolvable differences with [[Dino Cazares]], Vext parted with [[Divine Heresy]] in 2008. The highly publicised split left both the fans and the press confused. In an exclusive \"Metal Injection\" interview, Vext explained the real reasons behind his departure from the band: \n{{Quotation| I've been suffering the indignities of Dino's massive ego for as long as I've worked with him, and unfortunately, everything I've heard about him had eventually come to fruition, and he is exactly as he's been portrayed as by his ex-band members. And this happening now is the same reason why he's not in Fear Factory anymore. It was a stepping stone in my life and I'm moving on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2008/05/01/the-divine-heresy-soap-opera-continues/|title=THE DIVINE HERESY SOAP OPERA CONTINUES|date=1 May 2008|website=Metalsucks.com|accessdate=31 May 2016}}</ref> |Tommy Vext}}\n\nLater bassist Joe Payne and drummer [[Tim Yeung]] both broke ties with Dino and on July 27, 2015, in an interview with [[MetalSucks]], Cazares confirmed that he was the only remaining member of Divine Heresy.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2015/07/27/109-dino-cazares-of-fear-factory/ | title=#109: Dino Cazares of Fear Factory | publisher=[[MetalSucks]] | date=July 27, 2015 | accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Snot<ref name=\":0\" />===\n[[Snot (band)|Snot]] is an American [[Heavy metal music|metal]] band from [[Santa Barbara, California]]. Formed in 1995, the band released their debut studio album ''[[Get Some (album)|Get Some]]'' with founding vocalist [[Lynn Strait]] in 1997 and disbanded after his death in 1998. In 2008, the band reformed, with Vext on vocals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Reunited Snot Releases New Song, Announces Tour With DEVILDRIVER |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=102395 |publisher=[[blabbermouth.net]] |date=August 7, 2008 |accessdate=April 15, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081223014922/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=102395 |archivedate=December 23, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Snot has played a number of shows fronted by Vext, including a fall 2008 tour in the United States, supporting [[DevilDriver]]. When later original guitarist [[Sonny Mayo]] left the band, Snot went on hiatus again.\n\nOn February 11, 2014, Snot reunited the second time at the [[Whisky a Go Go]] in Hollywood.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/reunited-snot-to-play-first-show-in-five-years-next-month/ |title=Reunited SNOT To Play First Show in Five Years Next Month |date=January 13, 2014 |publisher=[[blabbermouth.net]] |accessdate=February 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/video-reunited-snot-plays-first-show-in-five-years/ |title=Video: Reunited SNOT Plays First Show In Five Years |date=February 15, 2014 |publisher=[[blabbermouth.net]] |accessdate=February 15, 2014}}</ref> This second reunion line-up once again featured Vext, Mayo, Doling, Fahnestock and Miller. They went on to play three more shows in the Southern California area before once again going quiet.\n\n=== Vext ===\nIn 2011 Tommy Vext reformed Vext with members of [[Mutiny Within]], (Bill Fore, and Andrew Jacobs); along with guitar virtuoso [[Angel Vivaldi]]. They released the EP titled ''Impermanence.'' in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.angelvivaldiofficial.com/about |title=angelvivaldi. &#124; o f f i c i a l w e b s i t e |publisher=Angelvivaldiofficial.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-30}}</ref>\nBy 2013 Vivaldi and Jacobs had left the project, with Billy DiNapoli taking over on guitars.  They released an EP ''Broke is the New Black''.<ref>{{cit web|url=http://rip-fred-marques.blogspot.com/2014/02/vext-broke-is-new-black-ep-2013.html |date= |accessdate=2018-10-29}}</ref>\n\nTommy then had gone on tour with [[Mayhem Festival]] '2013 as a cook, and moved to Los Angeles after the tour.\n\n=== Westfield Massacre<ref name=\":0\" />===\nAfter his stint with Snot, Vext moved on and formed a new band known as \"Westfield Massacre\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metalinjection.net/av/former-divine-heresy-members-launch-the-westfield-massacre/ |title=Westfield Massacre |date=April 29, 2016 |publisher=metalinjection.net |accessdate=April 29, 2016}}</ref> The band released their self-titled debut album on Urban Yeti Records 2016. In 2017, Vext began working on a side project with former [[DevilDriver]] drummer [[John Boecklin]] Vext left Westfield while he was on tour with Five Finger Death Punch.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theprp.com/2017/06/12/news/westfield-massacre-replace-frontman-tommy-vext-amid-drama/|title=Westfield Massacre |publisher=ThePrP.com|date=June 12, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n=== Bad Wolves ===\nIn 2016, Vext formed a new band, known as \"[[Bad Wolves]]\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.riffrelevant.com/2017/05/01/bad-wolves-pastpresent-westfield-massacre-god-forbid-devildriver-etc-members-premiere-learn-to-live-video/ |title=Bad Wolves |date=May 1, 2017 |publisher=riffrelevant.com |accessdate=May 1, 2017}}</ref> with former [[DevilDriver]] drummer [[John Boecklin]]. Guitarists Doc Coyle (Vagus Nerve, [[God Forbid]]) and Chris Cain ([[Bury Your Dead]]), and later, bassist Kyle Konkiel formerly of [[In This Moment]] were recruited for the project. During the summer of 2016, they entered AudioHammer Studios with longtime collaborator Mark Lewis ([[Trivium (band)|Trivium]], [[All That Remains (band)|All That Remains]]) and tracked what would become the group's debut studio album. On May 2, 2017, Bad Wolves independently premiered a song titled \"Learn to Live\" accompanied by a music video<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metalinjection.net/video/bad-wolves-ex-god-forbid-ex-devildriver-premieres-way-djenty-learn-to-live/ |title=Video: Learn To Live |date=May 2, 2017 |publisher=metalinjection.net |accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref> The video was streamed over 600,000 times. In November 2017, it was announced<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/bad-wolves-feat-former-devildriver-god-forbid-divine-heresy-members-debut-album-due-in-spring/\n  |title=Bad Wolves Get Signed |date=November 2, 2017 |publisher=Blabbermouth.net }}</ref> that Bad Wolves signed with [[Eleven Seven Music]] and [[Zoltan Bathory]], the founding guitarist of [[Five Finger Death Punch]], took them under his wings as the band's manager.\n\nThe band released their debut studio album, ''[[Disobey]]'' on May 11, 2018 through [[Eleven Seven Music]].<ref name=\"Loudwire\"/><ref name=\"Loudwire\">{{cite web | url=http://loudwire.com/bad-wolves-toast-to-the-ghost-new-song-debut-album/ | title=BAD WOLVES 'TOAST TO THE GHOST' IN NEW SONG, ANNOUNCE DEBUT ALBUM | website=Loudwire.com | date=3 November 2017 | accessdate=3 February 2018 | author=Hill, John}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theprp.com/2018/03/23/news/bad-wolves-share-acoustic-cover-zombie-detail-debut-album-disobey/|title=Bad Wolves Share Acoustic Cover Of \"Zombie\", Detail Debut Album \"Disobey\"|publisher=theprp.com|accessdate=March 23, 2018|date=March 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe album reached number 23 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. In May 2017, Bad Wolves released their debut single, \"Learn to Live\".<ref name=\"learn2live\">{{cite web|title=BAD WOLVES Feat. Former DEVILDRIVER, GOD FORBID, DIVINE HERESY Members: 'Learn To Live' Video Released|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/bad-wolves-feat-former-devildriver-god-forbid-divine-heresy-members-learn-to-live-video-released/|website=[[Blabbermouth]]|accessdate=2018-03-01|date=May 2017}}</ref> In November 2017, Bad Wolves released their second single, \"Toast to the Ghost\".<ref name=\"Loudwire\"/> On January 18, 2018, they released a third single, which was a cover of \"[[Zombie (song)#Bad Wolves version|Zombie]]\" (originally by [[The Cranberries]]), which charted on multiple [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' charts]].<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8097436/bad-wolves-cranberries-zombie-rock-charts | title=Bad Wolves' Cover of The Cranberries' 'Zombie' Roars Onto Rock Charts | website=Billboard.com | date=31 January 2018 | accessdate=3 February 2018 | author=Rutherford, Kevin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Bad-Wolves-Cover-of-The-Cranberries-ZOMBIE-Goes-Global-20180130 | title=Bad Wolves' Cover of The Cranberries' ZOMBIE Goes Global | website=Broadway World | date=30 January 2018 | accessdate=4 February 2018}}</ref> The night of her death, [[Dolores O'Riordan]] left a voice message to her friend, record label executive Dan Waite, where she offered to \"sing on it\" on the cover that Waite had previously given O'Riordan to listen to and accredit. [[TMZ]] published this voice message on April 5, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8289027/dolores-oriordan-cranberries-final-recording-voicemail-audio |title=Voicemail from Cranberries Singer Dolores O'Riordan Emerges |website=www.billboard.com|date=September 19, 2019 |accessdate=September 19, 2019}}</ref> A music video was released on February 22. The song topped the US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock Songs]] chart, while the music video was viewed more than 170 million times. The single is certified platinum in Canada and the United States and gold in Germany.\n\nThe band toured with [[Five Finger Death Punch]], [[Shinedown]], [[Breaking Benjamin]], and [[Starset]] for the first half of 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theprp.com/2018/02/06/news/five-finger-death-punch-shinedown-starset-bad-wolves-tour-announced/|title=Five Finger Death Punch, Shinedown, Starset & Bad Wolves Tour Announced {{!}} Theprp.com|date=2018-02-06|work=Theprp.com|access-date=2018-02-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\nBad Wolves became the first rock band in 2018 to reach platinum status for their cover song, \"[[Zombie (song)#Bad Wolves version|Zombie]]\".<ref name=\"Platinum\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/bad-wolves-video-of-zombie-platinum-plaque-presentation-in-camden-new-jersey/|title=BAD WOLVES: Video Of 'Zombie' Platinum-Plaque Presentation In Camden, New Jersey|accessdate=2018-09-06|date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Vext ===\n\n* 2004: ''Cast The First Stone''\n* 2012: ''Impermanence''\n\n=== God Forbid ===\n\n* 2004: ''[[Gone Forever]]'' (guest vocals on \"Soul Engraved\")\n\n=== Divine Heresy ===\n\n* 2007: ''[[Bleed the Fifth]]''\n\n=== Westfield Massacre ===\n\n* 2016: ''Westfield Massacre''\n\n=== Bad Wolves ===\n\n* 2018: ''[[Disobey]]''\n* 2019: ''[[N.A.T.I.O.N.]]''\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n* ''Twinkle Twinkle Little Star'' (short film) (2016) (as Drug Dealer)<ref>{{Citation|title=Twinkle Twinkle Little Star|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5535868/|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Commonscat}}\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vext, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American rock singers]]\n[[Category:African-American male singers]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "77.205.18.119", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Vext"}
